{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"echo 'Reading task board and research context.' && rg -n \\\"IQ-|Inference Queue|In Progress Ledger|WS[0-9]\\\" MASTER_TASKS.md | head -n 200 && ls -la ~/Documents/local-codebases/temple-sanhedrin/research || true\"","aggregated_output":"Reading task board and research context.\n17:  Q4_0 and Q8_0 quantization (all integer math). Float support deferred to WS10.\n24:  checkpoint is loggable by the Book of Truth ledger (WS13 in TempleOS MASTER_TASKS).\n44:### WS0 — Project Setup & Reference Material\n45:- [ ] WS0-01 Create project structure (src/, tests/, models/, docs/, automation/)\n46:- [ ] WS0-02 Document GGUF format spec (from llama.cpp/gguf-py reference)\n47:- [ ] WS0-03 Document Q4_0 and Q8_0 quantization math (integer-only formulas)\n48:- [ ] WS0-04 Document LLaMA architecture (layer structure, tensor names, dimensions)\n49:- [ ] WS0-05 Create reference output corpus (llama.cpp outputs for known prompts+seeds)\n51:### WS1 — Integer Math Foundations\n52:- [ ] WS1-01 Implement fixed-point arithmetic helpers (mul, div, shift, round)\n53:- [ ] WS1-02 Implement integer exp/log/sqrt approximations\n54:- [ ] WS1-03 Implement integer softmax approximation\n55:- [ ] WS1-04 Implement RMSNorm (integer path)\n56:- [ ] WS1-05 Add test harness for math functions (compare against reference)\n58:### WS2 — GGUF Parser\n59:- [ ] WS2-01 Implement GGUF header parser (magic, version, tensor count, metadata count)\n60:- [ ] WS2-02 Implement GGUF metadata reader (key-value pairs, string/int/float/array types)\n61:- [ ] WS2-03 Implement GGUF tensor info reader (name, dims, type, offset)\n62:- [ ] WS2-04 Implement tensor data loader (read quantized blocks from file into memory)\n63:- [ ] WS2-05 Add GGUF validation tool (print model info, tensor list, total size)\n65:### WS3 — Quantization Kernels\n66:- [ ] WS3-01 Implement Q4_0 block structure (32 values per block, 1 scale float16)\n67:- [ ] WS3-02 Implement Q4_0 dequantize (block -> integer array)\n68:- [ ] WS3-03 Implement Q4_0 dot product (quantized vec * quantized vec -> scalar)\n69:- [ ] WS3-04 Implement Q8_0 block structure and dequantize\n70:- [ ] WS3-05 Implement Q8_0 dot product\n71:- [ ] WS3-06 AVX2 optimized Q4_0 dot product (inline asm)\n72:- [ ] WS3-07 AVX2 optimized Q8_0 dot product (inline asm)\n73:- [ ] WS3-08 Benchmark: Q4_0 dot product ops/sec (naive vs AVX2)\n75:### WS4 — Matrix Operations\n76:- [ ] WS4-01 Implement naive matmul (quantized input, integer accumulator)\n77:- [ ] WS4-02 Implement row-major / col-major layout handling\n78:- [ ] WS4-03 AVX2 tiled matmul (cache-friendly blocking)\n79:- [ ] WS4-04 Implement element-wise operations (add, mul, scale)\n80:- [ ] WS4-05 Benchmark: matmul GOPS for typical LLM dimensions (4096x4096)\n82:### WS5 — LLaMA Forward Pass\n83:- [ ] WS5-01 Implement RoPE (Rotary Position Embedding) in integer math\n84:- [ ] WS5-02 Implement GQA (Grouped Query Attention) — Q/K/V projection, score, softmax, output\n85:- [ ] WS5-03 Implement SwiGLU FFN (gate * up projection, silu activation, down projection)\n86:- [ ] WS5-04 Implement transformer block (attention + FFN + residual + RMSNorm)\n87:- [ ] WS5-05 Implement full forward pass (embed -> N blocks -> final norm -> logits)\n88:- [ ] WS5-06 Implement KV cache for autoregressive generation\n89:- [ ] WS5-07 Validation: compare logits against llama.cpp for first token of known prompt\n91:### WS6 — Tokenizer\n92:- [ ] WS6-01 Implement BPE vocabulary loader from GGUF metadata\n93:- [ ] WS6-02 Implement BPE encode (text -> token IDs)\n94:- [ ] WS6-03 Implement BPE decode (token IDs -> text)\n95:- [ ] WS6-04 Handle special tokens (BOS, EOS, padding)\n96:- [ ] WS6-05 Validation: tokenize/detokenize round-trip matches llama.cpp\n98:### WS7 — Sampling & Generation\n99:- [ ] WS7-01 Implement temperature scaling on logits\n100:- [ ] WS7-02 Implement top-k sampling\n101:- [ ] WS7-03 Implement top-p (nucleus) sampling\n102:- [ ] WS7-04 Implement repetition penalty\n103:- [ ] WS7-05 Implement autoregressive generation loop (prompt -> tokens one at a time)\n104:- [ ] WS7-06 Implement `Inference(prompt, max_tokens, temp, top_k, top_p);` HolyC API\n106:### WS8 — Integration & Polish\n107:- [ ] WS8-01 End-to-end test: load TinyLlama Q4_0, generate 50 tokens, compare quality\n108:- [ ] WS8-02 Memory usage profiling and optimization\n109:- [ ] WS8-03 Book of Truth integration hooks (log model load, each token, anomalies)\n110:- [ ] WS8-04 Interactive mode with streaming token output to TempleOS console\n111:- [ ] WS8-05 Performance tuning: identify and optimize top-5 hottest functions\n112:- [ ] WS8-06 Documentation: user guide for loading models and running inference\n114:### WS9 — GPU Compute Partition (IOMMU-Safe, Book-of-Truth-Audited)\n118:- [ ] WS9-01 GPU threat model: DMA risks, firmware opacity, MMIO attack surface, IOMMU bypass vectors\n119:- [ ] WS9-02 IOMMU (VT-d/AMD-Vi) initialization and enforcement — mandatory, no GPU without it\n120:- [ ] WS9-03 GPU memory partition design — dedicated physical region, never overlaps kernel/log pages\n121:- [ ] WS9-04 Explicit copy-in/copy-out protocol — CPU copies tensors to GPU region, triggers compute, copies results\n122:- [ ] WS9-05 PCIe device enumeration in HolyC — discover GPU via config space, map BARs\n123:- [ ] WS9-06 GPU command submission interface — minimal ring buffer, no proprietary driver\n124:- [ ] WS9-07 MMIO register map for target GPU compute dispatch (start with virtio-gpu or simple compute)\n125:- [ ] WS9-08 Book of Truth hooks: log every DMA mapping, every GPU command, every MMIO write\n126:- [ ] WS9-09 GPU compute shader/kernel format — simple dispatachable compute tasks\n127:- [ ] WS9-10 Matmul offload: move quantized matrix multiply to GPU, keep results in GPU partition\n128:- [ ] WS9-11 Attention score computation offload to GPU\n129:- [ ] WS9-12 GPU error handling: timeout, hang detection, forced reset, logged to Book of Truth\n130:- [ ] WS9-13 Benchmark: GPU vs CPU inference speed for TinyLlama 1.1B Q4_0\n131:- [ ] WS9-14 Fallback: if no IOMMU available, GPU disabled entirely — CPU-only mode, no exceptions\n133:### WS10 — Multi-Architecture Model Support\n134:- [ ] WS10-01 Abstract forward pass interface — model-agnostic layer dispatch\n135:- [ ] WS10-02 Mistral architecture support (sliding window attention, different GQA config)\n136:- [ ] WS10-03 Qwen2 architecture support (different FFN layout, tied embeddings)\n137:- [ ] WS10-04 Phi-3 architecture support (different attention pattern, block structure)\n138:- [ ] WS10-05 Architecture auto-detection from GGUF metadata keys\n139:- [ ] WS10-06 Model registry: map GGUF architecture string to forward pass implementation\n141:### WS11 — Extended Quantization Support\n142:- [ ] WS11-01 Q5_0 and Q5_1 quantization (5-bit, wider dynamic range)\n143:- [ ] WS11-02 Q2_K, Q3_K, Q4_K, Q5_K, Q6_K (k-quant family, mixed precision)\n144:- [ ] WS11-03 IQ quantization formats (importance-based, variable bit-width per weight)\n145:- [ ] WS11-04 Quantization format auto-selection from GGUF tensor type field\n146:- [ ] WS11-05 Performance comparison matrix: tok/s vs quantization level vs model size\n148:### WS12 — Model Conversion & Preparation Tooling (Host-Side)\n151:- [ ] WS12-01 GGUF model validator — verify file integrity, tensor checksums, format version\n152:- [ ] WS12-02 Model preparation guide: download from Hugging Face → quantize → copy to TempleOS disk\n153:- [ ] WS12-03 Ollama model extraction: pull Ollama blob → extract GGUF → validate\n154:- [ ] WS12-04 Model size calculator: predict RAM/disk requirements before loading\n155:- [ ] WS12-05 Reference output generator: run llama.cpp on known prompts, save expected outputs\n157:### WS14 — safetensors Format Support (Hugging Face Native)\n158:- [ ] WS14-01 Document safetensors binary format (header JSON + raw tensor data, no pickle)\n159:- [ ] WS14-02 Implement safetensors 